     DDDDEEEESSSSCCCCRRRRIIIIPPPPTTTTIIIIOOOONNNN
          Unix _g_m_a_c_s is a text editor written by James Gosling at
          Carnegie-Mellon University, styled after the EMACS editors
          that exist on ITS, Twenex and Multics.  Invoking _g_m_a_c_s with
          a list of files causes gmacs to start up and do a vvvviiiissssiiiitttt----ffffiiiilllleeee
          on each of the named files.  For more information, read the
          User's Guide (see below).

          The command teach-gmacs(1) will put the user into gmacs in a
          self-instruction mode, allowing the user to learn by doing.

     DDDDOOOOCCCCUUUUMMMMEEEENNNNTTTTAAAATTTTIIIIOOOONNNN
          To see what documentation is available for gmacs, issue the
          command

               lf $TOOLS/lib/gmacs/man

          This will list the files that document the gmacs
          environment.  The contents of these files can be printed out
          using the _t_o_o_l_m_a_n command with a given subject as argument.
          (The subject is one of the above filenames with the "1." or
          ".1" stripped off.)

          Most gmacs man pages are short and can be displayed at the
          terminal.  The User's Guide, however, is extensive and
          should be printed on the Xerox 9700 by means of the command

               toolman -X gmacs_doc


     EEEENNNNVVVVIIIIRRRROOOONNNNMMMMEEEENNNNTTTT
          TERM identifies the terminal being used, either a _t_e_r_m_c_a_p
          entry, or a code to identify terminals to be handled
          specially.  Special terminals include _H_D_S _C_o_n_c_e_p_t (concept,
          c100, c108, c108r, concept108w), _D_E_C _V_T_1_0_0 (vt100), _A_n_n
          _A_r_b_o_r _A_m_b_a_s_s_a_d_o_r (amb, annarbor, aaa), _T_e_k_t_r_o_n_i_x _4_0_2_5
          (tek4025, 4025), _M_i_n_i_B_e_e (minibee), _I_n_f_o_t_o_n _4_0_0 (i400).

          TERMCAP identifies the termcap file containing the terminal
          definition to be used.  This variable is not needed if one
          of the special terminals listed above is used.

          EPATH is a path used when locating MLisp files to be loaded
          into gmacs with the _l_o_a_d command.  The default value is
          EPATH=":$TOOLS/lib/gmacs/maclib".




